04509nam a22007095i 9780228010227DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20212021xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280102277 a10.1515/97802280102272doi  a(DE-B1597)657968  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9199.3.S514bA6 2021 7aPOE0110002bisacsh04aC811/.542231 aShields, Carol, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Collected Poetry of Carol Shields /cCarol Shields; ed. by Nora Foster Stovel. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tBooks By Carol Shields -- tAfter Enlightenment -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Note on the Text -- tThe Collected Poetry of Carol Shields -- tThe Collected Poetry of Carol Shields -- tOthers, Intersect, and Coming to Canada -- tNew Poems (From Coming to Canada) -- tMary Swann’s Poems in Swann -- tSnow Poem Sequence -- t“Time Line” Poem Sequence -- tThe Sunday Poems -- tArchived Poems -- tAnnotations -- tWorks Cited0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCarol Shields, best known for her fiction writing, received both the Pulitzer Prize and the Governor General’s Award for Fiction for her novel The Stone Diaries. But she also wrote hundreds of poems over the span of her career.The Collected Poetry of Carol Shields includes three previously published collections and over eighty unpublished poems, ranging from the early 1970s to Shields’s death in 2003. In a detailed introduction and commentary, Nora Foster Stovel contextualizes these poems against the background of Shields’s life and oeuvre and the traditions of twentieth-century poetry. She demonstrates how poetry influenced and informed Shields’s novels; many of the poems, which constitute miniature narratives, illuminate Shields’s fiction and serve as the testing ground for metaphors she later employed in her prose works. Stovel delineates Shields’s career-long interest in character and setting, gender and class, self and other, actuality and numinousness, as well as revealing her subversive feminism, which became explicit in Reta Winter’s angry (unsent) letters in Unless and in the stories of poet Mary Swann and Daisy Goodwill in Swann and The Stone Diaries.The first complete collection of her poetry, this volume is essential for all readers of Carol Shields. Stovel’s detailed annotations, based on research in the Carol Shields fonds at Library and Archives Canada, reveal the poems in all their depth and resonance, and the dignity and consequence they afford to ordinary people.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCanadian poetryy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFeminist poetry. 7aPOETRY / Canadian.2bisacsh  aAmerican.  aCanadian.  aconflict.  acontemporary.  acouples.  afamily.  aform.  ageography.  aimagery.  aliterary genres.  amarriage.  amaturation.  ametaphor.  arelationships.  astructure.  asymbolism.  awomen.1 aStovel, Nora Foster, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStovel, Nora Foster, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aZwicky, Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978022801022740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228010227423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228010227/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles